<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900529-0145</DOCNO><DOCID>900529-0145.</DOCID><HL>   RTC Sells Horizon Financial Branches   As Bailout of Sandamp;L Industry Accelerates</HL><DATE>05/29/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9A</SO><CO>   MSL X.APS ZION</CO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Resolution Trust Corp. sold the 37branches of Horizon Financial, Southampton, Pa., to FirstValley Bank, Bethlehem, Pa., and Union National Bank ofPittsburgh.   The transaction was part of another block of thrift salesand takeovers, as the agency accelerates the Sandamp;L industrybailout.</LP><TEXT>   Horizon Financial had $1.76 billion in assets andliabilities of $2.1 billion. The RTC will receive premiums of$26.5 million from the two acquiring institutions. The RTCwill advance about $1.25 billion to the acquirers and willretain about $1.75 billion of the Horizon's assets. Theagency expects to recover some of the advances by selling theassets, and it estimated the ultimate cost of the transactionat $357.8 million.   Separately, the RTC placed Pima Savings andamp; LoanAssociation, Tucson, Ariz., and Mercury Savings andamp; LoanAssociation, Huntington Beach, Calif., into receivership. Theassets of Pima Savings totaled $2.7 billion, and the assetsof Mercury Savings totaled $2.2 billion.   The RTC also placed Caguas-Central Savings Bank of PuertoRico, with $1.7 billion in assets, and American PioneerSavings Bank, Orlando, Fla., with $1.8 billion in assets, inconservatorship. Caguas-Central Savings Bank is the firstthrift in Puerto Rico to be taken over by the RTC.   Under conservatorships, the institutions are managed bythe government but the owners maintain their interests in thethrifts. Under receivership, ownership interests are wipedout and the RTC prepares to sell off the thrift's assets.   In other actions by the RTC last week:   -- Mountainwest Savings andamp; Loan Association, Ogden, Utah,was sold to Mountainwest Financial, Sandy, Utah, a newlychartered subsidiary of Sears Consumer Financial Corp.Mountainwest Savings had assets of $155.3 million andliabilities of $211.4 million. The RTC will advance about$180 million to the acquirer and retain $128.4 million inassets. The agency expects the transaction ultimately to cost$65.1 million.   -- Deseret Savings andamp; Loan Association, Salt Lake City, wassold to Zions First National Bank, Salt Lake City, a unit ofZions Bancorporation. Deseret had assets of $131.8 millionand liabilities of $221.8 million. The RTC advanced $125.3million and retained $104.3 million in assets, and expectsthis transaction to cost $99.2 million.   -- The insured deposits of First Federal Savings andamp; LoanAssociation of Brenham, Texas, were transferred to KilgoreFederal Savings andamp; Loan Association, Kilgore, Texas. FirstFederal had $116.4 million in assets, and liabilities of$125.4 million. The RTC advanced $76.8 million, and expectsthe transaction to cost $36.8 million.   -- Remington Savings Association, Elgin, Texas, was placedin receivership. The thrift had $174.2 million in assets.</TEXT></DOC>